rname is the first letter of your first name followed by your last name. A person named \"Andrew Klassen\" would have the following as a username.\n\n        <b>aklassen</b>\n\nYour password will be provided to you from your administrator.\n\n4. When the following prompt appears select <b>connect</b>.\n\n[[File: continue.png]]\n\nIf you are connecting from an apple device you might be asked if you want to trust the certificate. This is normal, select the option to trust the certificate.\n\nIf you are using Ubuntu/Linux, connect using the following parameters.\n\n[[File: ubuntu_settings.png]]',_binary 'utf-8'),(82,'',_binary 'utf-8'),(83,'',_binary 'utf-8'),(84,_binary '<h2>Connecting to the Wifi</h2>\n\nEvery user is given a unique username and password for connecting to the wifi. If this is your first time connecting follow the instructions below.\n\n1. Click on the wireless icon located on the bottom right corner of the computer.\n\n[[File: connect.png]]\n\n2. You should see a list of wireless networks, select the one titled hope_matters. \n\n3. You will be prompted for a username and password. Your username is the first letter of your first name followed by your last name. A person named \"Andrew Klassen\" would have the following as a username.\n\n        <b>aklassen</b>\n\nYour password will be provided to you from your administrator.\n\n4. When the following prompt appears select <b>connect</b>.\n\n[[File: continue.png]]\n\nIf you are connecting from an apple device you might be asked if you want to trust the certificate. This is normal, select the option to trust the certificate.\n\nIf you are using Ubuntu/Linux, connect using the following parameters.\n\n[[File: ubuntu_settings.png]]\n\n<h2>Changing your password</h2>\n\n1. Login to http://database.hope.\n\n2. On the dashboard page select <b>Change Password</b>.\n\n[[File: dashboard.png]]\n\n3. Fill out the change password form selecting <b>wifi</b> as your account type.\n\n[[File: change_password.png]]\n\nAfter this point in the process your password has been changed. However, most operating systems cache or save wifi credentials. This means that your computer will be attempting to authenticate using the old credentials (and failing) until you explicitly tell it to forget the previous credentials.\n\n4. Do a start menu search for wifi settings, select <b>Change Wi-Fi settings</b>.\n\n[[File: wifi_settings.png]]\n\n5. Select the network that you want to forget and click <b>forget</b>. \n\n[[File: forget.png]]\n\n6. Connect to the network using your new credentials.',_binary 'utf-8'),(85,'',_binary 'utf-8'),(86,'',_binary 'utf-8'),(87,'',_binary 'utf-8'),(88,'',_binary 'utf-8'),(89,_binary '<h2>Overview</h2>\n\nAs organizations grow, they often create tools and programs to help them work more efficiently. However, the tools usually need to work with sensitive data. This causes the tool to become a security risk. Take a look at the following bash script.\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=bash>\n\n#!/bin/bash\n\nusername=\"jeff\"\npassword=\"milkman123\"\ndatabase=\"ticketsystem\"\n\nif [[ ! -z \"${2}\" ]]; then\n                	\n     mysql -u ${username} -p${password} -D ${database} -e \"UPDATE ticketServer_tickets SET blocked=\'1\' WHERE email =\'${2}\';\" 2> /dev/null\n\nelse\n     echo \'\'\n     echo \"What user?\"\n     echo \"syntax: onelife blockuser <email>\"\n     echo \'\'\nfi\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nNotice how the password is exposed in clear text. This is referred to as a hardcoded credential. Anyone who comes into contact with the script now has the database username and password.\n\nIn addition to the vulnerability, there is no centralized management of this credential. If the jeff account needed a password change, you would have to manually update every script. \n\n<h2>Password prompt method</h2>\n\nA simple and effective solution is to prompt the user for the password before the script is run. Below is a good example.\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=bash>\n\n#!/bin/bash