rsonalization Tool.  \n2.	Open the YubiKey Personalization Tool by doing a search for YubiKey Personalization Tool\n3.	Click on Static Password Mode\n4.	Click on Advance Mode\n5.	Insert YubiKey into USB slot.  (Y faces up)\n6.	Click on Configuration Slot 1\n7.	Read down to Password Parameters and advance the characters to 64\n8.	Click on Generate for Public Identity, Private Identity, and Secret Key.\n9.	Check mark Upper and lower case, Alphanumeric, and Send ! as prefix\n10.	Click  on Write Configuration\n11.	You will be asked to save the file.  Click Save\n12.	Your YubiKey is now configured with a 64 character password. To view and check, open notepad or a black document and push the Y on the Yubikey.  You should be able to see your password print in text on the notepad or blank document.  Do not save.  This is just to check the configuration.  \n13.	Delete the file you saved in step 11 and empty trash\nIf you want to configure another password, you can repeat the process for Configuration Slot 2\nUsing the Yubikey:\nWhen setting a password, put your Yubikey into the USB of your computer.  \n1.	When asked for a password.  Touch the Y on your Yubikey and the password that was configured on slot 1 will print in the password box.  Some sites will not allow 64 characters even though this is the ideal security measure.  \n2.	Continue to follow the prompts of the site that you are setting up.  Each time it asks for the password you will touch the Y on your Yubikey.  The benefit is that your password is very secure and you only have to remember to use your Yubikey.  You dont have to remember another password.\nYou have the option of programming two slots.  This means you have two unique passwords on your Yubikey.  To access them, touch the Y once for the first slot or password, and touch and hold the Y for the second slot or password.  If you use both passwords for things, you will have to remember which one you used for which site.  \nFor more security measures, you can set your password as above, but instead of using only the Yubikey, you can add your personal password first and then the Yubikey password to make it even longer.  This provides more security because you need both a personal password and a Yubikey to make the site accessible.  See example:  SunnyD: !6LVvu4vutklhjvgnvfdjuntffdiltiikhljjtvbcdbtvuddlchhreguhuvhvhbvv',_binary 'utf-8'),(102,_binary '===Setting up your Yubikey===\n===Yubikey Static programming===\n1.	Go to https://support.yubico.com/support/solutions/articles/15000006480-understanding-core-static-password-features and download the YubiKey Personalization Tool.  \n2.	Open the YubiKey Personalization Tool by doing a search for YubiKey Personalization Tool\n3.	Click on Static Password Mode\n4.	Click on Advance Mode\n5.	Insert YubiKey into USB slot.  (Y faces up)\n6.	Click on Configuration Slot 1\n7.	Read down to Password Parameters and advance the characters to 64\n8.	Click on Generate for Public Identity, Private Identity, and Secret Key.\n9.	Check mark Upper and lower case, Alphanumeric, and Send ! as prefix\n10.	Click  on Write Configuration\n11.	You will be asked to save the file.  Click Save\n12.	Your YubiKey is now configured with a 64 character password. To view and check, open notepad or a black document and push the Y on the Yubikey.  You should be able to see your password print in text on the notepad or blank document.  Do not save.  This is just to check the configuration.  \n13.	Delete the file you saved in step 11 and empty trash\nIf you want to configure another password, you can repeat the process for Configuration Slot 2\n===Using the Yubikey===\nWhen setting a password, put your Yubikey into the USB of your computer.  \n1.	When asked for a password.  Touch the Y on your Yubikey and the password that was configured on slot 1 will print in the password box.  Some sites will not allow 64 characters even though this is the ideal security measure.  \n2.	Continue to follow the prompts of the site that you are setting up.  Each time it asks for the password you will touch the Y on your Yubikey.  The benefit is that your password is very secure and you only have to remember to use your Yubikey.  You dont have to remember another password.\nYou have the option of programming two slots.  This means you have two unique passwords on your Yubikey.  To access them, touch the Y once for the first slot or password, and touch and hold the Y for the second slot or password.  If you use both passwords for things, you will have to remember which one you used for which site.  \nFor more security measures, you can set your password as above, but instead of using only the Yubikey, you can add your personal password first and then the Yubikey password to make it even longer.  This provides more security because you need both a personal password and a Yubikey to make the site accessible.  See example:  SunnyD: !6LVvu4vutklhjvgnvfdjuntffdiltiikhljjtvbcdbtvuddlchhreguhuvhvhbvv',_binary 'utf-8'),(103,_binary '===Setting up your Yubikey===\n===Yubikey Static programming===\n#	Go to https://support.yubico.com/support/solutions/articles/15000006480-understanding-core-static-password-features and download the YubiKey Personalization Tool.  \n#	Open the YubiKey Personalization Tool by doing a search for YubiKey Personalization Tool\n#	Click on Static Password Mode\n#	Click on Advance Mode\n#	Insert YubiKey into USB slot.  (Y faces up)\n#	Click on Configuration Slot 1\n#	Read down to Password Parameters and advance the characters to 64\n#	Click on Generate for Public Identity, Private Identity, and Secret Key.\n#	Check mark Upper and lower case, Alphanumeric, and Send ! as prefix\n#	Click  on Write Configuration\n#	You will be asked to save the file.  Click Save\n#	Your YubiKey is now configured with a 64 character password. To view and check, open notepad or a black document and push the Y on the Yubikey.  You should be able to see your password print in text on the notepad or blank document.  Do not save.  This is just to check the configuration.  \n#	Delete the file you saved in step 11 and empty trash\nIf you want to configure another password, you can repeat the process for Configuration Slot 2\n===Using the Yubikey===\n#When setting a password, put your Yubikey into the USB of your computer.  \n#	When asked for a password.  Touch the Y on your Yubikey and the password that was configured on slot 1 will print in the password box.  Some sites will not allow 64 characters even though this is the ideal security measure.  \n#	Continue to follow the prompts of the site that you are setting up.  Each time it asks for the password you will touch the Y on your Yubikey.  The benefit is that your password is very secure and you only have to remember to use your Yubikey.  You dont have to remember another password.\n\nYou have the option of programming two slots.  This means you have two unique passwords on your Yubikey.  To access them, touch the Y once for the first slot or password, and touch and hold the Y for the second slot or password.  If you use both passwords for things, you will have to remember which one you used for which site. \n \nFor more security measures, you can set your password as above, but instead of using only the Yubikey, you can add your personal password first and then the Yubikey password to make it even longer.  This provides more security because you need both a personal password and a Yubikey to make the site accessible.  See example:  SunnyD: !6LVvu4vutklhjvgnvfdjuntffdiltiikhljjtvbcdbtvuddlchhreguhuvhvhbvv',_binary 'utf-8'),(104,_binary '<h2>Overview</h2>\n\nAs organizations grow, they often create tools and programs to help them work more efficiently. However, the tools usually need to work with sensitive data. This causes the tool to become a security risk. Take a look at the following bash script.\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=bash>\n\n#!/bin/bash\n\nusername=\"jeff\"\npassword=\"milkman123\"\ndatabase=\"ticketsystem\"\n\nif [[ ! -z \"${2}\" ]]; then\n                	\n     mysql -u ${username} -p${password} -D ${database} -e \"UPDATE ticketServer_tickets SET blocked=\'1\' WHERE email =\'${2}\';\" 2> /dev/null\n\nelse\n     echo \'\'\n     echo \"What user?\"\n     echo \"syntax: onelife blockuser <email>\"\n     echo \'\'\nfi\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nNotice how the password is exposed in clear text. This is referred to as a hardcoded credential. Anyone who comes into contact with the script now has the database username and password.\n\nIn addition to the vulnerability, there is no centralized management of this credential. If the jeff account needed a password change, you would have to manually update every script. \n\n<h2>Password prompt method</h2>\n\nA simple and effective solution is to prompt the user for the password before the script is run. Below is a good example.\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=bash>\n\n#!/bin/bash\n\nread -s -p \"Password: \" password\n\nusername=\"jeff\"\ndatabase=\"ticketsystem\"\n\nif [[ ! -z \"${2}\" ]]; then\n                	\n     mysql -u ${username} -p${password} -D ${database} -e \"UPDATE ticketServer_tickets SET blocked=\'1\' WHERE email =\'${2}\';\" 2> /dev/null\n\nelse\n     echo \'\'\n     echo \"What user?\"\n     echo \"syntax: onelife blockuser <email>\"\n     echo \'\'\nfi\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nIn bash, the -s flag on read hides characters typed out by the user. Some languages have tools for dealing with passwords. Below is a <b>bad</b> example.\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=bash>\n\n#!/bin/bash\n\nusername=\"jeff\"\npasssword=${1}\ndatabase=\"ticketsystem\"\n\nif [[ ! -z \"${2}\" ]]; then\n                	\n     mysql -u ${username} -p${password} -D ${database} -e \"UPDATE ticketServer_tickets SET blocked=\'1\' WHERE email =\'${2}\';\" 2> /dev/null\n\nelse\n     echo \'\'\n     echo \"What user?\"\n     echo \"syntax: onelife blockuser <email>\"\n     echo \'\'\nfi\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\nThe script takes the first argument provided to the script as uses it as a password. This is bad for 2 reasons.\n\n1. the command with show up in the bash history <br>\n2. shoulder surfing is now possible\n\nIn some cases password prompting is not feasible. An example would be a backup script that runs at 2am every day.\n\n<h2>Secrets API Add Token (central password management)</h2>\n\nThe secrets feature of hope_matters has an API that allows you to access and decrypt sensitive information using an api token/key. Below are instructions to creating a token.\n\n1. Use the <b>generate key</b> feature to generate a key. Then, open the key and copy about 100 characters. The token can be any length. However, it provides you no benefit to use a shorter key because you are not memorizing it.\n\n2. ssh into the database server and run the following at the command line. Replace the phrase <b>token</b> with the 100 characters that you just copied.\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=bash>\n\nphp -r \"echo \\\"\\n\\\"; echo password_hash(\'token\', PASSWORD_ARGON2ID); echo \\\"\\n\\\";\"; history -d $((HISTCMD-1))\n\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n3. Copy the hash and open a database connection (phpmyadmin or workbench). Paste the hash under token_hash, set active to <b>yes</b>, and then provide a description for your token. Make sure you apply the changes.\n\nAt this point you have created an active token. However, tokens only have access to secrets that you give them access to.\n\n4. Create a new secret, the secret that you want to access using the token. Then, authorizes and view the secret. At the bottom of the page, provide your token as the password, make sure read only is checked, and click <b>Add Key</b>.\n\n6. Make sure to add the unhashed token as a secret, so you can remember it later.\n\n<h2>Using your Token</h2>\n\nYou can retrieve and decrypt the secret by posting the following values to the link below.\n\nhttp://<server>/api/get_secret.php\n\nid=<secret_id><br>\ntoken=<api_token>\n\n\n<b>Bash Example:</b><br>\nObviously, do not use 123 as a token.\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=bash>\n\n#!/bin/bash\n\nserver=10.0.0.249\ntoken=123\npassword=$(curl -s -d id=7 -d token=${token} -X POST http://${server}/api/get_secret.php)\n\necho $password\n\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n<b>PHP Example:</b><br>\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=php>\n\n<?php\n\n$post_string = \"id=7&token=123\";\n\n$opts = array(\'http\' =>\n    array(\n        \'method\'  => \'POST\',\n        \'header\'  => \'Content-type: application/x-www-form-urlencoded\',\n        \'content\' => $post_string\n    )\n);\n\n$context = stream_context_create($opts);\n$result = file_get_contents(\'http://10.0.0.249/api/get_secret.php\', false, $context);\n\necho $result;\n\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n\n<b>Python Example</b>\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=python>\n\n#!/usr/bin/env python3\n\nimport requests\n\nserver = \'10.0.0.249\'\ntoken = \'123\'\nurl = \"http://%s/api/get_secret.php\" % server\n\nresult = requests.post(url, data={\'id\': 7, \'token\': token})\nprint (result.text)\n\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n<b>Powershell Example</b>\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=powershell>\n\n$post_params = @{id=\'7\';token=\'123\'}\n$response = (Invoke-WebRequest -Uri http://10.0.0.249/api/get_secret.php -Method POST -Body $post_params).Content\nWrite-Host $response\n\n</syntaxhighlight>\n\n<b>VBA Example</b>\n\n<syntaxhighlight lang=bash>\n\nPublic Sub httpclient()\n\nDim xmlhttp As New MSXML2.XMLHTTP, myurl As String\n\nmyurl = \"http://10.0.0.249/api/get_secret.php\"\nxmlhttp.Open \"POST\", myurl, False\nxmlhttp.Send \"id=7&token=123\"\nMsgBox (xmlhttp.responseText)\n\nEnd Sub\n\n</syntaxhighlight>',_binary 'utf-8'),(105,_binary '* [[VeraCrypt]]\n* [[VPN]]\n* [[Custom Forms]]\n* [[Sensitive Info in Scripts]]\n* [[Adding DNS records]]\n* [[Network Overview 2019]]\n* [[Creating and using YubiKey]]',_binary 'utf-8'),(106,_binary '* [[VeraCrypt]]\n* [[VPN]]\n* [[Custom Forms]]\n* [[Sensitive Info in Scripts]]\n* [[Adding DNS records]]\n* [[Network Overview 2019]]\n* [[Network Details]]\n* [[Creating an